[The reference for the paper cited above is as follows: N Nathan, M Barry,
M Van Herp, H Zeller. Shortage of vaccines during a yellow fever outbreak
in Guinea. Lancet 2001; 358: 2129-30.
<http://www.thelancet.com/journal/vol358/iss9299/full/llan.358.9299.original
_research.18877.1>. The abstract reads as follows: "A yellow fever epidemic
erupted in Guinea in September, 2000. From 4 Sep 2000 to 7 Jan 2001, 688
instances of the disease and 225 deaths were reported. The diagnosis was
laboratory confirmed by IgM detection in more than 40 patients. A mass
vaccination campaign was limited by insufficient international stocks.
After the epidemic in Guinea, the International Coordinating Group on
Vaccine Provision for Epidemic Meningitis Control decided that 2 million
doses of 17D yellow fever vaccine, being stored as part of a UNICEF
stockpile, should be used only in response to outbreaks." - Mod.CP
